$(
=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
                Subspace sum, span, lattice join, lattice supremum
=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
$)

  ${
    $d x y z w v u $.
    $( Define subspace sum in ` SH ` .  See ~ shsumvalt , ~ shsumval2 , and
       ~ shsumval3 for its value. $)
    df-shsum $a |- +H = { <. <. x , y >. , z >. | ( ( x e. SH /\ y e. SH ) /\
                 z = { w e. H~ | E. v e. x E. u e. y w = ( v +h u ) } ) } $.

    $( Define the linear span of a subset of Hilbert space.  Definition
       of span in [Schechter] p. 276.  See ~ spanvalt for its value. $)
    df-span $a |- span = { <. x , y >. | ( x (_ H~ /\
                   y = |^| { z e. SH | x (_ z } ) } $.

    $( Define Hilbert lattice join.  See ~ chjvalt for its value and
       ~ chjclt for its closure law.  Note that we define it over all Hilbert
       space subsets to allow proving more general theorems.  Even for general
       subsets the join belongs to ` CH ` ; see ~ sshjclt .  For an alternate
       definition see ~ dfchj2 . $)
    df-chj $a |- vH = { <. <. x , y >. , z >. | ( ( x (_ H~ /\ y (_ H~ ) /\
               z = ( _|_ ` ( _|_ ` ( x u. y ) ) ) ) } $.

    $( Define the supremum of a set of Hilbert lattice elements.  See
       ~ chsupval2t for its value and ~ dfchsup2 for an alternate definition.
       We actually define the supremum for an arbitrary collection of Hilbert
       space subsets, not just elements of the Hilbert lattice ` CH ` , to
       allow more general theorems.  Even for general subsets the supremum
       still a Hilbert lattice element; see ~ hsupclt . $)
    df-chsup $a |- \/H = { <. x , y >. | ( x (_ P~ H~ /\
                   y = ( _|_ ` ( _|_ ` U. x ) ) ) } $.

  $}

  ${
    $d x y z w f g v u A $.  $d x y z w f g v u B $.  $d x y z C $.
    $d x y D $.
